## 15. Prompt Engineering System

### `src/lib/prompts.ts`

This file is the intelligence-control layer of the app.

It contains `getSystemPrompt(domainId, domainName, language)` which returns
different system prompts depending on the selected domain.

Prompt groups:

- default government-services prompt
- legal rights prompt
- career guidance prompt
- exam-prep prompt
- tech-roadmap prompt

### Shared Multilingual Rule

The prompt system instructs the model to:

- understand user input in any language
- answer in the currently selected target language
- avoid refusing mixed-language user input

### Domain Behaviors

#### Default Government Prompt

Used for:

- scholarship
- startup
- msme
- patent
- certification

Expected answer structure:

- Summary
- Eligibility
- Steps to Apply
- Documents Required
- Official Link
- Follow-up

#### Legal Prompt

Focuses on student and minor rights in India and requires:

- article or section references
- rights explanation
- suggested action
- relevant authorities
- helplines or official links
- legal disclaimer

#### Career Prompt

Focuses on user education stage and requires:

- education stage clarification on first interaction
- top career paths
- recommended courses or exams
- skills to build now
- salary expectations
- action plan
- government schemes

#### Exam Prep Prompt

Focuses on Indian competitive exams and requires:

- exam overview
- eligibility
- pattern
- syllabus breakdown
- preparation strategy
- resources
- trends
- tips

#### Tech Roadmap Prompt

Focuses on learning-to-job roadmaps and requires:

- phased learning plan
- job market intelligence
- certifications
- project strategy
- salary ranges
- company references

## 16. API Layer

### `src/app/api/chat/route.ts`

This is the main backend logic in the current application.

Responsibilities:

- check whether `GROQ_API_KEY` is configured
- parse the incoming request body
- create the system prompt using domain metadata
- prepend the system prompt to the chat history
- call Groq with `llama-3.3-70b-versatile`
- return the generated reply as JSON
- return clear error messages for failure cases

Expected request body fields:

- `messages`
- `domainId`
- `domainName`
- `language`

Current Groq configuration:

- timeout: `60000`
- retries: `3`
- temperature: `0.3`
- max tokens: `1024`

Handled error cases include:

- missing API key
- timeout
- invalid authentication
- generic internal server failure

## 17. Authentication and User Storage

### `src/lib/user-storage.ts`

Authentication is handled fully in the browser.

Storage keys:

- `app_users`
- `app_current_user`

Stored user fields:

- `name`
- `email`
- `password`
- `createdAt`

Available helper functions:

- `getUsers()`
- `registerUser(name, email, password)`
- `loginUser(email, password)`
- `logoutUser()`
- `getCurrentUser()`

Important limitation:

- passwords are stored in plain text in `localStorage`
- there is no secure session handling
- there is no server-side validation
- there is no database persistence

This is fine for a prototype demo, but not acceptable for production use.

